value.value: A small salivary gland located within the aerodigestive tract.
A benign or malignant neoplasm affecting the parathyroid glands.

label.value: Minus End of the Actin Filament

value.value: The end of an actin filament that is polymerizing at a slower rate.
The end of a microtubule where nucleation occurs.
A thin space between the outer and inner mitochondrial membranes formed by an invagination of the inner mitochondrial membrane.
The area that is internal to the inner mitochondrial membrane.
A detectable particle containing phospholipids, protein and calcium found in the mitochondrial matrix.
The conical central core located in the cochlea, which contains the cells of the spiral ganglion.
A grinding tooth with a broad crown; located behind the premolars.

label.value: Molecular Layer of the Cerebral Cortex

value.value: The superficial layer of the cerebral cortex, containing nerve fibers, neuroglial cells, and occasional horizontal cells of Cajal.

A lymphocyte derived most often from a pre-germinal center B cell, less often from a post-germinal center B cell. It is characterized by an abundant pale cytoplasm, indented nuclei with inconspicuous nucleoli, and open chromatin. It is found in the marginal zones of lymph nodes adjacent to the subcapsular and intermediary sinuses.
A rounded prominence of adipose tissue overlying the pubic symphysis and adjacent pubic bone.

A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the parotid gland.  Representative examples of benign neoplasms include Warthin tumor, monomorphic adenoma, and pleomorphic adenoma.  Representative examples of malignant neoplasms include carcinoma, lymphoma, and sarcoma.

label.value: Motor Nucleus of the Trigeminal Nerve

value.value: An aggregation of CN V cell bodies located in the mid-pons at the level of attachment of the trigeminal nerve to the brainstem; it is the origin of special visceral efferent (motor) fibers that innervate the muscles of mastication.
Salivary glands that produce and secrete a saliva made up exclusively of mucous.

label.value: Multiform Cell Layer of the Cerebral Cortex

value.value: The innermost layer of the cerebral cortex. It consists of numerous small neurons, small pyramidal cells, stellate cells, especially superficially and fusiform cells in deeper part whose axons project into the white substance of the cerebral cortex hemisphere
A nerve cell with several processes, usually an axon and three or more dendrites.
A membrane-bound vesicle that encompasses several smaller membrane-bound vesicles.

label.value: Muscle and Fasciae of the Thorax

value.value: Any of the skeletal muscles and/or fibrous tissue located in the thorax.
Any of a number of muscles that attach to the coccyx, including the pubococcygeus, ileococcygeuys, coccygeus muscles.
Muscles arising in the zygomatic arch that close the jaw.
Either one of the two muscles located in the middle ear: the tensor tympani or the stapedius muscle.
A thin layer of smooth muscle fibers found as a part of the tunica mucosa in the gastrointestinal tract and urinary bladder deep to the lamina propria mucosae.
A triangular muscle in the back, connected to the vertebral column, arm, and shoulder. Its action involves adduction, medial rotation, and extension of the arm.
A muscle cell precursor. It is essential for muscle repair.

A contractile cell found between the secretory cells and basement membrane of exocrine glands. Each myoepithelial cell has long cytoplasmic processes that wrap around a secretory unit. The contraction of the myoepithelial processes forces the secretory product from the secretory unit into its duct.

A spindle-shaped cell that exhibits characteristics of both fibroblasts and smooth muscle cells. It has an elongated nucleus and does not have basal lamina. The cytoplasm can be distinguished from the surrounding matrix because of actin filaments, myosin and other muscle proteins arranged to suggest a contractile ability.
Fibrillar protein polymers found in the contractile apparatus of muscle cells.

label.value: Myoid Portion of the Inner Segment of the Photoreceptor Cell

value.value: The portion of the inner segment of a photoreceptor cell between the ellipsoid portion and the nucleus that is rich in ribonucleic acids (RNA) and is a major site for protein synthesis.
The cutaneous plate on the dorsal surface of the distal end of a finger or toe.
One of two small oblong bones placed side by side at the middle and upper part of the face.
Any one of the neck or facial muscles controlling movement of the nose.
Any nerve supplying innervation to the external nose and nasal cavity.

Fibromatosis arising from the soft tissues of the penis. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped fibroblasts, and an infiltrative growth pattern.  It causes the penis to bend when it becomes erect.
The thin wall between the two nasal cavities.
A tube-like structure that conveys tears from the lacrimal sac to the nasal cavity.
An oval-shaped bone of the tarsus found on the medial side of the foot.
Any skeletal muscle located in the neck.
The constriction on the proximal end of the humerus between the head and the greater tubercle.
Small nerve fibers that innervate blood vessels.

A layer of nerve cells in the retina. Embryologically, it is part of the brain. Incoming light passes through nerve-fibres and intermediary nerve cells of the neural retina, before encountering the light-sensitive rods and cones at the interface between neural retina and the pigmented retinal epithelium.
The heaviest of the three major types (NF-L, NF-M, NF-H) of intermediate filament subunit proteins, which has a molecular weight of approximately 120 kDa.
The least heavy of the three major types (NF-L, NF-M, NF-H) of intermediate filament subunit proteins, which has a molecular weight of approximately 60 kDa.
The second heaviest chain of the three major types (NF-L, NF-M, NF-H) of intermediate filament subunit proteins, which has a molecular weight of approximately 100 kDa.
A benign, borderline, or malignant neoplasm that affects the penis.  Representative examples include penile hemangioma, penile intraepithelial neoplasia, and penile carcinoma.
A granular basophilic substance, which consists of granular endoplasmic reticulum and ribosomes, found in the cell bodies of neurons and dendrites.
A site of slightly thickened desmosomes in the stratum spinosum of the epidermis.
The gaps formed between myelin sheath segments along axons of certain neurons that serve to facilitate the rapid conduction of nerve impulses.
Any surface area on a bone that makes contact with soft tissues, like muscles and connective tissues, rather than forming a joint with another bone.
